For a basic system though, this *does* wokr. I think I'll trim down the module I wrote for playtesting so my players can get back to LANCER as we originally were playing... they seem ancy and need to fight in big mechs, not just summon them. We'll leave the simulation next time.

I based the "avatars" (as I've called them) off the players' mechs for this. I think in terms of playing a Persona style game, this is *close* but would need some additional work for creating the actual summons and making them interesting both narratively and mechanically

Finally, we were using a standard deck of cards on Roll20 to play, but the original vision uses tarot cards to make moves. There would need to be some work done around the Major Arcana that I haven't fully realized.

While this is the most complete any of my side projects has been, I'm not sure it'll get completed. We'll see. There's a lot of formatting that would need to be done and some finicky bits that I'm not so hot at writing.

I like the system as it sits for play. There's a lot of work I'd have to do to publish it, but right now it's about two pages of rules. I think a finished version would land closer to ten pages to include character creation and scene setting.

My LANCER players chose to do an "experimental" mission where they're playtesting this for me. I think it went okay overall, but I'm not sure it's what some of the gang wanted to do, which is understandable.

I know there is so much happening in the world right now, and the emotions of one person are often overlooked, but it has already made a difference in my mood. Separate from social media, talk to someone, and see a therapist. I can’t recommend it enough.
… therapist because even quick summaries of the situation, she was able to address my concerns and showed a willingness to go and learn more after our conversation.

I still dread appointments sometimes, and I’m not an open book with my feelings. I know I have several issues I haven’t discussed with my therapist yet, but now I *have* that outlet and I have a safe place. Today gave me an additional level of confidence that I have the right…

This level of professional conversation shows that my fears are larger than my friend group. While I see everyone posting online, there’s a level of disconnection that the format of social media presents. 

I grew up scoffing at the idea of therapy, but it truly helps me

Having therapy today was a very well timed event after yesterday’s deluge of bad news. While my therapist wasn’t informed on all the events, she listened, learned, and addressed the same fears I had without me sharing them first.

Remember to take care of yourself. Don’t get stuck doomscrolling all of the bad news.

Your mental health is important! You need not feel guilty pulling away from the news for a while.🏳️‍⚧️❤️

Just didn’t seem to do the trick for me. Souls is a different genre than DnD, and it really shows those differences in play.

I’m only halfway through the episode as I’m tweeting this, but I very deeply feel that, as many have said before me, they should have either used a different system or written a new one. The Souls games are already RPGs, so the groundwork is there! But squeezing into 5e —

I understand even that isn’t perfect, but since 5e makes a big deal out of needing free hands to do this or that, then make it readable! Especially in DS where I may swap to my Puromancy Flame or 2H my long sword. You could even do:

Armor: 16
Shield: +2
Total: 18

Base: 10
Armor: +6 (chain mail)
Dex Bonus: N/A
Shield: +2
Total AC: 18

I get that this makes it feel more “math-y” but if you’re going to have the option or need to remove the shield at some point, this shows you “okay, my ac is 16 without it” at a glance.

Some of this can be mitigated by a player who has taken the time and energy to memorize or vigilantly note take, but imagine if the sheet broke down the equation for you with blanks for each piece. Let’s say for example, you wear chain mail. It could look like:

—for what you gain and lose by swapping. 
Tbh, this is already a gripe I’ve had with 5e. Is this player’s AC 15 or 13 without a shield? They don’t remember how they calculated it, now we need to dive through what they have equipped to reverse engineer it.

Equipment management also feels clunky. The games always were about having a couple items quickslotted to swap to or to go from one to two handing weapons, and while I can feel the idea in play, it almost feels like there should have been more of an emphasis made on the sheet—

The Cleric class began with a chime, one of the spell focuses for Miracles, and if the player hit with it, they could spend position to heal another player some position. This heal is not nearly as big as the spell Heal, but it is a cool secondary ability!

Pieces of equipment have special abilities! Somewhat like Weapon Arts from DS3, some items let you spend position for bonus effects. For example: one character is dual wielding, and if he lands a hit with his scimitar(?) he can spend a few position for an extra swing.

Position is great! Having a “pool of energy” instead of Hit Points is a good change of pace. Being able to spend it on attack rolls OR damage rolls does help reflect the choices made in Souls like, “I’m going to get hit, but I’ll also hit them hard.”

So, I’m watching High Rollers play their review copy of the #DarkSouls #ttrpg and I have to say, I really think that fifth edition is holding it back.

There’s some fun ideas in here and I think it could have been more, but using 5e’s stats and proficiency breaks the souls feel.

@GabeJamesGames I’m interested to see more. I think it’ll ultimately be more appealing to the hardcore combat groups. I think the groups I play with would only be into this for shorter games, rather than whole campaigns.
Oops, I went back and read more. They mentions abilities gained from your character class. I was hoping they would make it classless, but it seems they really are using 5e to its fullest.

Or even tensions rising in the group. I think a system like this is way more suited for one-shot scenarios. “We fight through this ONE dungeon, we win” while the TTRPG genre is still about progressing in spite of failure.

Oh, I got so distracted I forgot to add:

I do think it’ll be a fun combat system. Souls always have good systems. But they’re not great environments for newbies. I worry that if someone is still learning combat, it’ll lead to them dying a lot and getting discouraged-

I personally enjoy the Souls games casually. Their combat *does* feel good, and their world has lore that’s discoverable in fun ways, but overall it’s a depressing world where it doesn’t matter WHO the player is, only whether or not they’re strong enough.

Anyways, all that to say I think this will evolve the combat side of the game, but leave role play behind. That’s how the Souls games are and that’s what their community cares about. Stats. Fighting. Weapons/Armor.
Streamers will play the game that their followers know. Writers make adventures for the game people know, on the marketplace that’s easy to find.

That’s the reason why so many people look for indie games. Not because DnD is bad, but because it is, at it’s heart, a wargame that the community took and evolved. DnD has Big Brand Recognition, which is why it continues to dominate the space.

Is that bad? No! 
DnD is as popular as it is because it’s a game that tries (despite itself) to give both role play and combat, and personally I believe it’s current success is due to how it got presented by streamers and other personalities.

Regardless of my individual opinion, I do think this project will be a major success, but it absolutely won’t have the popularity that DnD has. The success of this game will be from a pre-established fan base that I think will learn towards combat instead of role-play (oops,🧵🪡)

I was really scared when we started last night, but by the end, I am now looking forward to playing more!

Lancer is a cool system, and I can’t wait for more sci-fi shenanigans!

This game has been fun and frightening to set up as well because I’ve always been a fantasy nerd, and now here I am hosting a sci-fi mech game for three people who have lived much more in sci-fi or mech fiction than me.

But that’s just part of the process!! Luckily my players were willing to be flexible, so while there were things we couldn’t locate the rules to, we made temporary judgements and they’re willing to change once we have found the rules.

It really makes a difference when you’ve listened to an actual play show of the system before you play a game, is my takeaway here! I was a bit frustrated when we started because I felt I wasn’t running the game well and I thought that I just didn’t read the rules well enough,

Realized that Lancer is the first TTRPG system I’m learning that I’ve had no previous exposure to. When we played last night, combat was suuuuuuper slow because we kept looking things up, but by the end, it was starting to click.

Turns out, no one likes being in a cage. Animals are just like people: they have emotions and needs. Most pets are already limited to living in an apartment, so don’t make their entire world smaller with cages. 

You wouldn’t like being locked in a coat closet all day, would you?

As I got older, my family stopped putting the dogs in the crates at night or when we left. They taught the dogs to still use them as beds, but left the doors open.

Surprising no one: the dogs were much happier.

My parents crate trained our dogs when I was young and it never sat well with me. 
“It’s their bed. Their own room!” 

My bed doesn’t have bars on it that lock me in. My room is large enough for me to walk around. 

Animal crates are more the size of a coat closet to a human.
